                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Upper Rectus Abdominis</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The upper rectus abdominis is located in the upper abdominal region. It flexes the spine, bringing the ribcage towards the pelvis. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the standing ab wheel rollout, this muscle stabilizes the torso and maintains a straight body line. When you extend and return to the starting position, </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC385260/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">the upper rectus abdominis is highly activated</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This activation builds strength and stability in the upper core, which is essential for core development and improving abdominal definition.</span></p><h3><b>Lower Rectus Abdominis </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The lower rectus abdominis is located in the lower abdomen. It aids in spinal flexion and pelvic stabilization. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the standing ab wheel rollout, it maintains core stability and prevents lower back arching. High activation occurs when extending and returning to the starting position. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Strengthening the lower rectus abdominis enhances overall core performance, contributing to better balance and posture. Proper engagement of this muscle is essential for supporting lower back health and improving overall functional strength.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Overall, there is a high </span><a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/280003842_Muscle_Activation_Pattern_During_Isometric_Ab_Wheel_Rollout_Exercise_in_Different_Shoulder_Angle-Positions_2015" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">muscle activation rate</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> of 98.5% for the entire rectus adominis muscle during this exercise.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                                        <section class="exc-secondary">
                <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container bd-bot">
                        <div class="muscle-title">
                            <h2>Secondary Muscle Groups</h2>
                        </div>
                        <div class="muscle-list secondary-muscle">
                                                            <div class="secondary-item muscle-item">
